19
00:01:38,539 --> 00:01:44,090
to political reasons rather than
affordability issues. On the second hand,

20
00:01:44,090 --> 00:01:49,079
public services are often not looking
for profit, but are rather runned as a cost

21
00:01:49,079 --> 00:01:56,149
center. We distinguish three main sources
of revenues, national government, local

22
00:01:56,149 --> 00:02:01,079
government, end users which can be the
residents themselves or private

23
00:02:01,079 --> 00:02:06,399
enterprises. The national governments
often assigne grants and subside to

24
00:02:06,399 --> 00:02:10,679
supplement local revenues, since in most
municipalities in developing countries

25
00:02:10,679 --> 00:02:13,700
these are insufficient to cover all the
operation and maintenance

26
00:02:13,700 --> 00:02:18,980
costs. This is a case in Cameroon,
where the national government subsidizes

27
00:02:18,980 --> 00:02:24,379
85% of the operation and
maintenance costs. Local governments

28
00:02:24,379 --> 00:02:28,810
obtain their revenues from a variety of
sources, such as property taxes often

29
00:02:28,810 --> 00:02:33,660
based on the property size, as it happens
in Belo Horizonte Brazil, Delhi India,

30
00:02:33,660 --> 00:02:41,489
Dhaka Bangladesh or from other municipal fees,
parking fees, for instance and fines,

31
00:02:41,489 --> 00:02:42,590
as it happens

32
00:02:42,590 --> 00:02:49,140
in Ghorahi Nepal and Quezon City Philippines.
Depending on the tax money to cover the

33
00:02:49,140 --> 00:02:53,720
cost of municipal solid waste management
is often difficult, because as mentioned

34
00:02:53,720 --> 00:02:58,069
before, tax money is needed for a large
variety of urban services and it

35
00:02:58,069 --> 00:03:05,390
requires hard negotiations to get
the amounts needed. But also tax recovery

36
00:03:05,390 --> 00:03:10,090
is often difficult, given the inadequate
property systems in rapidly

37
00:03:10,090 --> 00:03:14,810
urbanizing cities with expanding
informal settlements where actually only

38
00:03:14,810 --> 00:03:19,440
a small proportion of the residents
actually pay taxes.

39
00:03:19,440 --> 00:03:23,540
Besides payment of waste service through
property taxes might be suitable if it

40
00:03:23,540 --> 00:03:28,380
is clearly stipulated that 
certain portion of the tax is earmarked

41
00:03:28,380 --> 00:03:33,230
to cover the cost of such service as it
is a case in Bamako Mali and Bangalore India. 

42
00:03:33,230 --> 00:03:39,109
Ok, so we now saw that national and 
local governments can put

43
00:03:39,109 --> 00:03:44,650
money, but users can also be charged
directly for the service. This is called

44
00:03:44,650 --> 00:03:49,459
direct charging. This is done in many
cities such as CaneteNepal Peru, 

45
00:03:49,459 --> 00:03:56,590
Kunming China, Lusaka Zambia or Nairobi in Kenya.
These charges can be sent to the users

46
00:03:56,590 --> 00:04:00,799
on a weekly, monthly or yearly basis or
directly charged after the collection 

47
00:04:00,799 --> 00:04:06,150
crew collects the waste as shown in the
pictures. User charges have the

48
00:04:06,150 --> 00:04:10,579
advantage that they can raise public
awareness about the real cost of the

49
00:04:10,579 --> 00:04:16,180
service and they tend to make the
service accountable. User charges can

50
00:04:16,180 --> 00:04:21,560
either be a flat rate. Everybody pays the
same. Attached to other utility bills,

51
00:04:21,560 --> 00:04:25,480
water bill, sanitation, phone, security,
electricity bill,

52
00:04:25,480 --> 00:04:31,100
which increases willingness to pay and
reduces billing costs. Or related to the

53
00:04:31,100 --> 00:04:35,790
quantity of waste discarded, which may
serve as incentive for waste prevention.

54
00:04:35,790 --> 00:04:43,020
This is also called pay as you throw. As
a general principle any increase in fees

55
00:04:43,020 --> 00:04:46,840
needs to be credible and connected to
real improvements in the waste

56
00:04:46,840 --> 00:04:50,910
management service, that are well
communicated to the citizens and

57
00:04:50,910 --> 00:04:55,330
actually perceived as such by them. Otherwise
users may choose to stop

58
00:04:55,330 --> 00:04:59,880
payment.Let's say for example they
promised to increase collection frequency

59
00:04:59,880 --> 00:05:05,310
from once per month to once per week. If
this never happens, 

60
00:05:05,310 --> 00:05:10,200
users would never pay on a weekly basis.
But if it does, they will probably be

61
00:05:10,200 --> 00:05:16,310
willing to do so. In any case, generally
collection of user charges for waste

62
00:05:16,310 --> 00:05:21,370
services is extremely low. Not everyone is
willing to pay or able to pay. 

63
00:05:21,370 --> 00:05:26,120
Consequently three very important
aspects need to be considered.

64
00:05:26,120 --> 00:05:33,690
Affordability, cost recovery and
willingness to pay. 

65
00:05:33,690 --> 00:05:38,020
How much can people afford for waste management services in
developing countries? It has been

66
00:05:38,020 --> 00:05:42,110
suggested that a practical upper limit
for affordable waste management costs is

67
00:05:42,110 --> 00:05:49,530
1% of per capita income level.
In low and middle-income countries with

68
00:05:49,530 --> 00:05:53,610
income levels below 1000$ per
capita per year,

69
00:05:53,610 --> 00:05:58,240
these works out to be around 10$ or less
per capita per year.

70
00:05:58,240 --> 00:06:05,230
It comes as no surprise that some low-
and middle-income countries set their

71
00:06:05,230 --> 00:06:11,990
user charges below full cost recovery
rates. Cross subsidizing could be an

72
00:06:11,990 --> 00:06:16,830
option to solve this. User charges allow
cross subsidizing between high income

73
00:06:16,830 --> 00:06:21,930
areas and low income areas. This happens
in Moshi Tanzania and 

74
